    <h1>&lambda;-bench variance: same prompt, five different runs</h1>
    <p class="summary">A single benchmark number is the average. Five runs on the same prompt show the variance — which is the part the average hides.</p>
  </header>

  <p class="lead">Repeating the same prompt against the same model is not redundant. It exposes what a single trial cannot:</p>
  <ul class="lead-list">
    <li>Whether the model takes the same path twice.</li>
    <li>Whether the errors it catches are the same errors.</li>
    <li>Whether success comes from a stable strategy or a lucky sample.</li>
  </ul>
  <p class="lead">These five charts are the same Sonnet 4.6 model, run on the same prompt — implement a beta-normalizer for Scott-encoded de Bruijn lambda terms in pure lambda calculus. Low effort, default settings. All five solutions pass the official 10-test LamBench suite.</p>
  <p class="lead"><a href="https://github.com/VictorTaelin/lambench" target="_blank" rel="noopener">LamBench</a> measures whether a model can solve these tasks — run the prompt, check the output against the test suite, record pass or fail. We ran the same prompt against Sonnet five times instead, and looked at the thinking trace each run produced. The model's output is probabilistic; the same input produces a different trace every time. A pass/fail number tells you whether the model solved the task. Five traces start to show <em>how</em> it solved the task — and how much that varies.</p>

