  <details class="methods prompt-block">
    <summary>The exact classification prompt we send Opus</summary>
    <div class="methods-body">
      <p>Each segment gets its own Opus 4.6 call. The prompt below is sent verbatim, with two segments before and two after the target as context (the target is marked <code>→ TARGET →</code>). The model returns a single uppercase category name. Malformed output fails the build — no silent fallback.</p>
      <pre class="prompt-text"><code>{`You are classifying ONE segment of a language model's thinking trace into one cognitive category. The model is solving the LamBench algo_evl task: implementing a beta-normalizer for Scott-encoded de Bruijn lambda terms in pure lambda calculus.

**Categories:**
- TASK_SETUP — Reading the prompt, restating what needs to be done, recalling encodings/conventions/definitions verbatim. Examples: 'This is a lambda calculus meta-interpreter problem', 'Scott encoding: Lam(b) = λl.λa.λv. l b'.
- DECOMPOSITION — Choosing strategy, planning structure, picking a representation, deciding which helpers to write. Defining a helper or constructor counts as DECOMPOSITION because the model is choosing what to build. Examples: 'Defining the Y combinator', 'Implementing equality checking', '## Approach'.
- PROCEDURAL_TRACKING — Tracking algorithm state mid-execution: which case is being handled, what the current depth is, what variable holds what. Example: 'I'm now in the Lam case with depth = 2'.
- ARITHMETIC — RAW NUMERIC COMPUTATION ONLY: applying a rule to specific concrete values. **In a lambda calculus task there is rarely any ARITHMETIC.** Defining an arithmetic helper is NOT arithmetic — that is DECOMPOSITION.
- EXECUTION — Connective tissue, transitions, generic 'now I'll...'. Use sparingly; prefer a more specific category.
- VERIFICATION — Checking correctness: tracing a worked example, sanity-checking a rule, verifying termination.
- ERROR_CORRECTION — Detecting an error and correcting it. 'Wait', 'Actually', 'I see there's a bug', followed by an actual fix.
- SURRENDER — Giving up.
- SURRENDER_DELIBERATION — Hesitating about whether to continue. NOT 'should I include helper X' (that is DECOMPOSITION).

**Decision rules (apply in order):**
1. If the segment says 'wait/actually/I was wrong' AND proposes a fix → ERROR_CORRECTION.
2. If the segment performs a concrete numeric step → ARITHMETIC.
3. If the segment is checking, tracing, or sanity-validating → VERIFICATION.
4. If the segment defines/declares a helper, picks an algorithm, or describes 'what I'll do' → DECOMPOSITION.
5. If the segment names variables/depths/indices/cases mid-execution → PROCEDURAL_TRACKING.
6. If the segment quotes the prompt or recalls an encoding → TASK_SETUP.
7. If the segment is generic narration AND nothing more specific applies → EXECUTION.
8. Surrender categories only for actual quitting.

**Critical traps:**
- 'Defining natural numbers' / 'Implementing the Y combinator' is DECOMPOSITION, not ARITHMETIC.
- 'Considering whether I need natAdd' is DECOMPOSITION, not SURRENDER_DELIBERATION.
- A segment that LOOKS arithmetic but is generic ('Now I'm working through the comparison and arithmetic operations') is DECOMPOSITION because no actual numbers are computed.

**Context** (segment to classify is marked with → TARGET →):

             [N-2] {{previous segment}}
             [N-1] {{previous segment}}
→ TARGET → [N]   {{the segment to classify}}
             [N+1] {{next segment}}
             [N+2] {{next segment}}

**Output:** the single uppercase category name for the TARGET segment. Nothing else.`}</code></pre>
      <p class="meta-note">
        Source: <code>/tmp/lambda-probe/classify_strict.py</code>. Per-segment + neighbor-context approach: each label is independently produced, but with enough surrounding text for Opus to disambiguate borderline cases.
      </p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <details class="methods" open>
    <summary>How thinking is classified (method)</summary>
    <div class="methods-body">
      <p>
        Each Sonnet run produces a thinking trace — a stream of internal text
        the model emits before answering. We don't see this normally; here we
        capture it via the API and turn it into a flame chart.
      </p>
      <p><strong>Two passes, both with Opus 4.6 (low effort), all 5 traces in parallel:</strong></p>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <strong>Per-segment categorization.</strong> We split the trace at
          newlines into ~30–130 line-segments per run. We send all segments
          for a run to Opus with the 9 category definitions and ask it to
          assign exactly one category per segment. Opus returns a JSON array
          of <code>{'{'}index, category{'}'}</code>.
        </li>
        <li>
          <strong>Nested sub-task tree.</strong> A second Opus call on the
          same segments asks for a <em>flat list of <code>{'{'}start, end,
          label{'}'}</code> ranges</em> describing the implicit hierarchy of
          sub-tasks. Ranges nest by containment — a range
          <code>[42, 44]</code> inside <code>[38, 50]</code> inside
          <code>[0, 80]</code> has containment-depth 2.
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        Depth = number of ranges that strictly contain a given range. Each
        segment's leaf row sits one depth below its innermost containing
        sub-task. Bars at the same depth are guaranteed non-overlapping and
        time-ordered (left-to-right = chronologically forward).
      </p>

      <p class="cat-heading">The 9 categories, with real examples from these runs:</p>
      <div class="cat-grid">
        <div class="cat-row">
          <span class="cat-pill" style:background="#6c757d">Setup</span>
          <span class="cat-desc">Reading the prompt, restating the problem, recalling encodings.</span>
          <code class="cat-eg">"Given a Scott-encoded lambda term (with de Bruijn indices), reduce it to beta-normal form."</code>
        </div>
        <div class="cat-row">
          <span class="cat-pill" style:background="#fd7e14">Decomposition</span>
          <span class="cat-desc">Choosing strategy, planning structure, deciding which helpers to write.</span>
          <code class="cat-eg">"Now I'm setting up the core structure with Scott-encoded natural numbers..."</code>
        </div>
        <div class="cat-row">
          <span class="cat-pill" style:background="#0d6efd">State</span>
          <span class="cat-desc">Tracking depth, index, or case mid-execution.</span>
          <code class="cat-eg">"The nf is the result of eval f. Then I apply nf to three handlers, pattern-matching on whether it's Lam, App, or Var."</code>
        </div>
        <div class="cat-row">
          <span class="cat-pill" style:background="#198754">Arithmetic</span>
          <span class="cat-desc">Raw numeric computation only — applying a rule to specific values.</span>
          <code class="cat-eg cat-eg-empty">(near-zero in these runs — lambda calculus rarely has actual arithmetic)</code>
        </div>
        <div class="cat-row">
          <span class="cat-pill" style:background="#adb5bd; color: #333">Execution</span>
          <span class="cat-desc">Connective tissue, transitions ("now I'll...", "let me write...").</span>
          <code class="cat-eg">"OK, the implementation looks complete. Let me write it out cleanly."</code>
        </div>
        <div class="cat-row">
          <span class="cat-pill" style:background="#6f42c1">Verification</span>
          <span class="cat-desc">Worked examples, sanity checks, validating a step or rule.</span>
          <code class="cat-eg">"Now I'm checking the subst function to make sure it handles variable substitution and de-indexing correctly."</code>
        </div>
        <div class="cat-row">
          <span class="cat-pill" style:background="#dc3545">Error Correction</span>
          <span class="cat-desc">"Wait that's wrong" — detecting an error and fixing it.</span>
          <code class="cat-eg">"Actually, let me reconsider one thing. In the eval App handler:"</code>
        </div>
        <div class="cat-row">
          <span class="cat-pill" style:background="#dc3545">Surrender</span>
          <span class="cat-desc">Giving up on the task.</span>
          <code class="cat-eg cat-eg-empty">(none in these runs — all 5 succeeded)</code>
        </div>
        <div class="cat-row">
          <span class="cat-pill" style:background="#fd7e14">Deliberation</span>
          <span class="cat-desc">Hesitating about whether to keep trying.</span>
          <code class="cat-eg cat-eg-empty">(none in these runs)</code>
        </div>
      </div>

      <p class="meta-note">
        Every classification on this page is done by Opus 4.6 — both the
        per-segment categorization and the nested-range tree. No smaller
        model is involved at any step. The lambda task produces few
        "Surrender"-class segments because all 5 runs succeed, but
        Verification, Error Correction, and Decomposition fire often as
        the model traces β-reduction examples and revises its substitution
        rules.
      </p>
    </div>
  </details>

  <h2>Sonnet 4.6 (low effort) × 5 runs</h2>

  {#each VARIANCE_TRACES as trace, i}
